        <description>Introduction By the fundamental theory of algebra, a general polynomial of the form,
$$ \tag{1} f(x) = a_{n}x^{n} + a_{n-1}x^{n-1} + \cdots + a_{1}x + a_{0} = 0 $$
has at least $ n $ complex roots (not necessarily unique). Therefore, given a root $ \alpha $ of the polynomial, we can rewrite $ (1) $ as,
$$ f(x) = (x - \alpha) f^&amp;rsquo;(x) = 0 $$
where $ f^&amp;rsquo;(x) $ is a polynomial of degree $(n - 1)$.</description>
        
